Tutorial 1 - Node to Deno

6 steps

In this tutorial, you will discover why Deno aims to improve upon Node.js and why it is a compelling choice for your future web projects. We will explore the motivations behind Deno's development and, most importantly, guide you through creating your very own cute Dino!

Finally, the tutorial will conclude with installation instructions to prepare you for the next steps in your learning journey.

Let's begin soaring with Deno!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

This campaign will only cover Linux or MacOS platforms. If you are a Windows user, please use GitHub Codespaces for a uniform and streamlined developer experience.

Prerequisites

  • It is recommended that you have Javascript and Typescript knowledge. It's not a strict requirement but it helps your learning journey.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • It is recommended that you have Javascript and Typescript knowledge. It's not a strict requirement but it helps your learning journey.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Gain insight into the principles and goals that drive Deno's development, including its focus on security, simplicity, and modern tooling.
  • Explain how Deno embraces modern JavaScript and TypeScript features allowing easy-to-write clean, maintainable code.
  • Understand Deno's secure-by-default model, including how permissions work and the implications for application development.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: What is Deno?

    Deno is a Javascript runtime that supports Typescript and is backwards-compatible with Node projects. It also supports WebAssembly. It also comes with a package manager that supports JSR and npm packages.

    But first, let's learn a little history about Deno.

    Creator of Node Creator of Deno

    Deno started as a project to solve some of the glaring design issues Node had during its development.

    The creator of Node AND Deno is one person, Ryan Dhal. He thought about how he regretted his design decisions for Node.

    Some of his decisions that he regretted are:

    • The removal of promises, which are necessary for async/await. 
    • Lack of permissions and access control. In theory, this can allow a compromised Javascript project malicious control over your computer. 
    • Outdated build system. Node still uses GYP which is already abandoned for GN in V8 (via Chromium).

    Watch the following YouTube video from JSConf 2018 where he talks about the 10 things he regretted about Node.js.

    Ryan Dahl and his team also created V8 bindings in Rust for the Deno runtime. Check out his blog post about releasing the stabilised V8 bindings in Rust. It's such a cool read!

    However, some of the proposed ideas during the talk are now untrue, such as

    • No npm compatibility 
    • No node_modules compatibility 
    • No package.json support

    Deno is still a worthwhile effort to bring the best experience to the Javascript ecosystem.

    From NodeJS To Deno

    The screenshot above is related to the joke that Deno is Node sorted out. It was shown as an easter egg in this YouTube video.

    Since then, Deno's development has greatly advanced. Years of progress have demonstrated that Deno has kept improving its ecosystem and tooling such as the Deno runtime, command-line tools, and Typescript support.

    When building projects, developers who will purely use Deno won't have to configure a lot such as TSConfig for Typescript compiler configuration, ESLint for Typescript linting, and Prettier for formatting code.

    Gone are the days of scattered configuration files! You can now have one deno.json file that handles configuration for linting, formatting, dependency management, and package publishing.

    One pain point with Deno before was the lack of Node and npm support on projects out of the box. But with the release of Deno 2.0, Deno now has backwards compatibility with Node projects, increasing its adoption in the Javascript ecosystem.

  • Step 2: ESM and CJS

    The Javascript ecosystem has CommonJS (CJS) as a specification for writing modules in Javascript. It started as a way to write code for server-side Javascript. Here is an example that uses CJS syntax to bring modules into scope.

    const dotenv = require("dotenv");

const main = () => {
	console.log(dotenv().FOO);
}

module.exports = { main };
    TypeScript

    Today, the current Javascript ecosystem is now moving towards a new specification to write modules called ECMAScript Modules (ESM). An ESM variant of the previous code snippet uses ESM syntax to bring modules to the namespace.

    import { dotenv } from "dotenv";

const main = () => {
	console.log(dotenv().FOO)
}

export default main;
    TypeScript

    There is still debate if developers should choose CommonJS (CJS) or ECMAScript Modules (ESM).

    But to keep the ongoing adoption of newer modern standards, Deno highly encourages developers to migrate towards ESM. Deno has CJS support because of the backwards-compatibility it has for Node and npm.

    What do you think? Do you still use CJS over ESM? Why? Share your thoughts in our Discord forum channel.

  • Step 3: Native Typescript Support

    Deno does not need third-party tooling on transpiling/compiling Typescript into Javascript.

    Transpiling is transforming one language into another i.e. Typescript to Javascript. This is different from a similar process called compiling when code is transformed into machine code which is readily fed through the CPU or any processing unit. The two are used interchangeably a lot but it's good to know the differences first.

    In Deno, Typescript Compiler (TSC), Speedy Web Compiler (SWC) and other similar tools, are transpilers. But for now, let's just use the term compiler to avoid confusion with their documentation.

    The most probable reason why it is still called a compiler was the analogy between Javascript and assembly. You can think of Javascript as the "assembly of the web". Thus, it actually makes sense to also call it a compiler instead of a transpiler.

    Deno comes with its compiler that has full Typescript support with built-in type-checking. This allows developers to build projects without the need for other tools for linting and type-checking. Typically, here is a high-level process of how most compilers do it.

    Because Deno has a built-in Typescript compiler, developers do not need to install tools such as TSC, SWC and other similar tools. You can just run any Typescript file without the need to compile it into a Javascript file.

  • Step 4: Installing Deno

    For the sake of uniformity in this campaign, we require users to use a Unix-like operating system like MacOS or Linux. Windows users can use GitHub Codespaces to have a Linux environment.

    Preparing Your GitHub Codespaces

    This section is exclusively for those users who want to use a cloud environment, specifically, GitHub Codespaces.

    If you are already familiar with how to use other cloud environments or are currently using WSL or MacOS, you are free to skip this section to head over to the Installing Deno section.

    This campaign will only cover instructions for GitHub Codespaces and not other cloud environment providers. Head to the documentation to learn more about GitHub Codespaces.

    Creating A GitHub Account

    If you already have a GitHub Account, feel free to move over to the next section of this step.

    GitHub Codespaces require a GitHub Account. If you have not created a GitHub Account, sign up here. Once you have your GitHub Account, you can start creating a new repository.

    Creating A New Repository

    To create a new repository, log in to your GitHub dashboard at https://github.com using your GitHub Account credentials.

    Look towards the upper right corner of the page. You should see a plus button with a down triangle. Click the plus button and it should drop down a list of options like this screenshot below.

    Next, click the "New repository" button. It should redirect you to a new page.

    Then follow the steps from the screenshot below.

    Once the repository is created, click the "<> Code " button (usually, it's coloured green). It should give you a dropdown with a toggle for Local or Codespaces. Click "Codespaces" then click "Create codespace on main". Look at the screenshot below for reference.

    It should take you to a cloud environment using VSCode Web as the interface. Deno is not installed there by default so let's do that in the next step.

    Installing Deno

    This section works for users that use a local MacOS/Linux environment or GitHub Codespaces.

    To install Deno, head to their website https://deno.com and scroll down a bit. You will see an Install Deno section with the commands to install precompiled binaries for Deno.

    Here is a sample command for installing Deno in MacOS/Linux from their website.

    Once you run the command, you will be prompted with "Edit shell configs to add deno to the PATH?". Type "Y" and press Enter.

    You may also want to install shell completions. Press the space bar to select or deselect. Press Enter.

    Be sure to close your current terminal and open a new terminal so the updated environmental variables get loaded.

    You may encounter an error when selecting Bash for completions. That's because the install script tries to install it in a directory that requires root access. For a workaround, run the following commands.

    mkdir -p ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions
deno completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/deno

    This should give you the completions you need when writing the deno command then pressing the space bar key then pressing the Tab key on your terminal.

    You can check that Deno is properly installed by running the following command.

    deno upgrade

    As of writing, Deno's version is 2.0.6.

    Disclaimer: You are free to install Deno in any fashion like building from source or using your system's package manager. Ensure that the builds work and have a version of at least 2.0.6. However, those methods will not be included in the campaign.

  • Step 5: Secure By Default with Deno

    Deno is secure by default. It disallows running scripts and processes that require local file system and network access. For these scripts and processes to run, they require explicit command flags or user intervention.

    Let's experiment with that by first creating a Deno project. For local users, run the following command.

    deno init soar-with-deno
cd soar-with-deno
deno run main.ts

    For GitHub Codespaces users, run the following command.

    deno init .
deno run main.ts

    It should give you an output with no errors.

    There is a difference in the set of commands since GitHub Codespaces users are already in the root directory of the soar-with-deno project. Take note of this .

    Next, if you are using VSCode, head to https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=denoland.vscode-deno and install the Deno extension. This should help you get proper code completions and other features such as Deno's LSP.

    Edit the main.ts file by replacing all of its contents with the following code.

    if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve((_req_) => {
    (async () => {
      for await (const el of Deno.readDir(".")) {
        console.log(el.name);
      }
    })();
    const hello = new Response("Hello, World!");
    return hello;
  });
}
    TypeScript

    You should get the following prompt like the screenshot below.

    Press "Y" and then press Enter for the first prompt, you will now have a running HTTP server with Deno.serve.

    Open a new terminal and run the following command.

    curl http://0.0.0.0:8000  # or http://localhost:8000

    You will notice that your curl command seems to be on pause or waiting for a response. That's because if you go back to the terminal where your deno command is running, you will receive another prompt like the screenshot below.

    Press "Y" and then press Enter, it should output all the files and directories in your project directory.

    You should get a "Hello, World!" output on your terminal where you ran the curl command.

    See the screenshot below to check that you have received the same output.

    Any user can circumvent the first prompt by running the following command.

    deno run --allow-net main.ts

    The --allow-net flag has a short variant, -N.

    For the second prompt, you can add the flag --allow-read or its short variant -R.

    This design is intentional because, in Node, users are not prompted with what the script or process has access to such as network access, files and directories read and write access, and running other scripts access.

    This secure-by-default design in Deno prevents unwanted access from foreign code without the knowledge of the user. By adding a sandbox such as containers and VMs, this design also helps increase the security of your projects.

    This design encourages good security practices and ensures users are informed about what scripts have access to.

  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    Woah! You finally reached the end of this tutorial. Now, head out to https://deno.com.

    Then click the "Make your own dino!" button. Play around or randomise the colours and outfits for your Dino!

    If you are done, share your Dino to our Discord forum channel! Share what you think about Deno! Discuss and learn with other Stackies!
